  "text": "The SASL broker-side authentication in Apache Kafka is centered around these key components: (1) **SaslServerAuthenticator** - the main broker-side authenticator that implements the Authenticator interface, handles the SASL handshake protocol, mechanism negotiation, and manages the authentication state machine lifecycle. (2) **SaslChannelBuilder** - wires up the SASL infrastructure, creates SaslServerAuthenticator instances, registers SASL providers (PlainSaslServerProvider, ScramSaslServerProvider, OAuthBearerSaslServerProvider), and configures server-side callback handlers per mechanism. (3) Mechanism-specific SASL servers: **PlainSaslServer** (implements javax.security.sasl.SaslServer for PLAIN), **ScramSaslServer** (for SCRAM-SHA-256/512), and **OAuthBearerSaslServer** (for OAUTHBEARER). GSSAPI/Kerberos uses the JDK's built-in SASL server with **KerberosLogin** managing the Kerberos TGT. (4) Mechanism-specific callback handlers: **PlainServerCallbackHandler**, **ScramServerCallbackHandler**, and the generic **SaslServerCallbackHandler**. (5) Authentication context lifecycle: **AuthenticationContext** interface -> **SaslAuthenticationContext** implementation, used by **DefaultKafkaPrincipalBuilder** to build KafkaPrincipal from SASL authentication results. Supporting infrastructure includes **ScramMechanism** (enum defining SCRAM variants), **CredentialCache** (stores SCRAM credentials on broker), **SaslInternalConfigs** (re-authentication config), and the provider classes that register mechanisms with the JCA.",
